    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-02T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-02T12:00:00-05:00" n="447"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d447">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/565</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-03T02:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 3, 1918, 2 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.55 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Replying to your November 30, 7 p.m. It would seem to me extremely unwise under
                    present circumstances to modify our position that the Chinese Eastern should be
                    considered as a portion of the main line of Trans-Siberian Railway system. If we
                    confine ourselves to the use of the Amur Railway, as suggested by the Consulate
                    at Vladivostok, we would practically admit Japan’s claim of succession to
                    Russia’s rights in the Chinese Eastern. The plan agreed to by Japan, as reported
                    in my December 2, 10 p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d447fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    providing for Allied supervision with <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName> as executive chief to assist in operation of the entire
                    system, is far better.</p>
                <p>Replying to your November 23, 2 p.m. The plan now suggested by Japan does not
                    specify any definite time of Allied supervision and assistance. I think public
                    statement should be issued by Allied committee when organized, explaining its
                    purpose and stating definitely that it will continue only so long as the Russian
                    management requires assistance. <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName>
                    believes that in a reasonable time good working Russian organization can be
                    built up.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
